3. PERMITTED USES
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

You may:

a) use, run, inspect, and study the Software for Non-Commercial Use;

b) modify the Software locally for personal testing, research, evaluation,
   debugging, security review, or experimentation;

c) create private forks solely for Contribution Purpose;

d) create public forks only when technically necessary to submit pull requests,
   patches, or Contributions to the original Project;

e) submit Contributions to the original Project;

f) discuss, review, benchmark, audit, and research the Software, provided that
   such activity does not involve publishing, hosting, distributing, promoting,
   or maintaining an unauthorized Independent Fork or Derivative Work;

g) create tutorials, articles, videos, documentation, or educational materials
   about the Software, provided that such materials do not distribute an
   unauthorized Fork or Derivative Work and do not misrepresent affiliation with
   the Project.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
4. CONTRIBUTION-ONLY FORKS
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Forks are permitted only for Contribution Purpose.

A Fork must be primarily intended to test, improve, fix, document, audit, or
contribute back to the original Project.

A public Fork is permitted only to the extent reasonably necessary to submit
pull requests, patches, issues, or other Contributions to the original Project.

A public Fork must not be presented, promoted, branded, advertised, maintained,
or developed as:

a) an independent project;

b) an alternative version;

c) a community edition;

d) a continuation;

e) a successor;

f) a replacement;

g) a competing implementation;

h) a separately maintained version;

i) a substantially similar product;

j) or an unofficial distribution intended for general users.

If a public Fork is no longer being used for active Contribution Purpose, the
Maintainers may request that the Fork be made private, archived, or removed.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
5. PROHIBITED INDEPENDENT FORKS AND CLONES
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

You may not, without prior written permission from the copyright holder:

a) publish, distribute, host, promote, maintain, or develop an Independent Fork;

b) create or distribute a public clone of the Software as a separate project;

c) create or distribute a competing version of the Software;

d) create or distribute a community edition, alternative edition, unofficial
   edition, continuation, successor, replacement, or variant of the Software;

e) use the Software to build or maintain a separately developing project;

f) use the Software to create a substantially similar product or experience;

g) use the Software as the basis for a project that competes with, replaces, or
   diverts users from the original Project;

h) solicit users, contributors, sponsors, or community members away from the
   original Project using a Fork or Derivative Work based on the Software.

Legitimate Contributions to the original Project are allowed. Separately
developing Forks are not allowed.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
6. NO SUPERFICIAL VARIANTS
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

You may not create, publish, distribute, host, promote, or maintain a Fork,
clone, Derivative Work, adaptation, remix, or variant that preserves the core
concept, structure, source code, prompts, assets, user experience,
architecture, interaction model, or distinctive behavior of the Software while
changing only superficial or secondary details.

Superficial or secondary details include, but are not limited to:

a) project name;

b) character names;

c) character personality;

d) themes;

e) prompts;

f) wording;

g) visual design;

h) branding;

i) configuration;

j) user interface details;

k) minor behavior changes;

l) assets;

m) documentation;

n) repository layout.

Changing these details does not make an unauthorized Fork or Derivative Work
permitted.

Meaningful improvements must be directed toward the original Project unless
separate written permission is granted by the copyright holder.

